18 March 1985\n| 25 April 2001\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Slovakia}} Slovakia\n| \n| 28 May 1993 d (previously ratified by {{flag|Czechoslovakia}} on 7 July 1988)\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Slovenia}} Slovenia\n| \n| 16 July 1993 a\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Somalia}} Somalia\n| \n| 24 January 1990 a\n|-\n| {{flagicon|South Africa}} South Africa\n| 29 January 1993\n| 10 December 1998\n|-\n| {{flagicon|South Sudan}} South Sudan\n| \n| 30 April 2015 a\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Spain}} Spain\n| 4 February 1985\n| 21 October 1987\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Sri Lanka}} Sri Lanka\n| \n| 3 January 1994 a\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Sudan}} Sudan\n| 4 June 1986\n| \n|-\n| {{flagicon|Swaziland}} Swaziland\n| \n| 26 March 2004 a\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Sweden}} Sweden\n| 4 February 1985\n| 8 January 1986\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Switzerland}} Switzerland\n| 4 February 1985\n| 2 December 1986\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Syria}} Syrian Arab Republic\n| \n| 19 August 2004 a\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Tajikistan}} Tajikistan\n| \n| 11 January 1995 a\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Thailand}} Thailand\n| \n| 2 October 2007 a\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Macedonia}} The Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia\n| \n| 12 December 1994 d\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Timor-Leste}} Timor-Leste\n| \n| 16 April 2003 a\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Togo}} Togo\n| 25 March 1987\n| 18 November 1987\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Tunisia}} Tunisia\n| 26 August 1987\n| 23 September 1988\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Turkey}} Turkey\n| 25 January 1988\n| 2 August 1988\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Turkmenistan}} Turkmenistan\n| \n| 25 June 1999 a\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Uganda}} Uganda\n| \n| 3 November 1986 a\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Ukraine}} Ukraine\n| 27 February 1986\n| 24 February 1987 (ratified as the {{flag|Ukrainian SSR}})\n|-\n| {{flagicon|UAE}} United Arab Emirates\n| \n| 19 July 2012 a\n|-\n| {{flagicon|UK}} United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland\n| 15 March 1985\n| 8 December 1988\n|-\n| {{flagicon|USA}} United States of America\n| 18 April 1988\n| 21 October 1994<ref name=\"untc\" /><ref name=\"USA-State-Department\">{{cite web \n|title=Convention against Torture and Other Cruel, Inhuman or Degrading Treatment or Punishment - Addendum to Initial reports of States parties due in 1995\n|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/documents/organization/100296.pdf\n|website=U.S. Department of State |publisher=U.S. Department of State |accessdate=10 December 2018}}</ref> ([[Torture and the United States#History of U.S. Accession|With specific reservations detailed here.]]) As of 10 December 2018, the United States of America is not party to the 2002 [[Optional Protocol to the Convention against Torture and other Cruel, Inhuman or Degrading Treatment or Punishment|Optional Protocol]].<ref name=\"UN-OPCAT\">{{cite web\n|title=9.b Optional Protocol to the Convention against Torture and Other Cruel, Inhuman or Degrading Treatment or Punishment\n|url=https://treaties.un.org/Pages/ViewDetails.aspx?src=TREATY&mtdsg_no=IV-9-b&chapter=4&clang=_en\n|website=United Nations Treaty Collection |publisher=United Nations |accessdate=10 December 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Uruguay}} Uruguay\n| 4 February 1985\n| 24 October 1986\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Uzbekistan}} Uzbekistan\n| \n| 28 September 1995 a\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Vanuatu}} Vanuatu\n| \n| 12 July 2011 a\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Venezuela}} Venezuela (Bolivarian Republic of)\n| 15 February 1985\n| 29 July 1991\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Vietnam}} Viet Nam\n| 7 November 2013\n| 5 February 2015\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Yemen}} Yemen\n| \n| 5 November 1991 a\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Zambia}} Zambia\n| \n| 7 October 1998 a\n|}\n\n== Optional Protocol ==\n{{Main|Optional Protocol to the Convention against Torture}}\n[[File:OPCAT members.svg|thumb|400px|{{legend|#008000|states parties}}\n{{legend|#00ff00|states that signed, but have not ratified}}\n{{legend|#e0e0e0|states that have not signed}}</div>]]\nThe [[Optional Protocol to the Convention against Torture and other Cruel, Inhuman or Degrading Treatment or Punishment]] (OPCAT), adopted by the General Assembly on 18 December 2002 and in force since 22 June 2006, provides for the establishment of \"a system of regular visits undertaken by independent international and national bodies to places where people are deprived of their liberty, in order to prevent torture and other cruel, inhuman or degrading treatment or punishment,\"<ref>[[Optional Protocol to the Convention against Torture and other Cruel, Inhuman or Degrading Treatment or Punishment|OPCAT]], Article 1.</ref> to be overseen by a Subcommittee on Prevention of Torture and Other Cruel, Inhuman or Degrading Treatment or Punishment.\n\nAs of October 2016, the Protocol has 76 signatories and 90 parties.<ref name=\"UN-OPCAT\" />\n\n== Committee against Torture ==\n{{Multiple issues|section=yes|\n{{update|date=July 2018|section}}\n{{advertisement|section|date=April 2020}}\n{{COI|section|date=April 2020}}\n{{external links|section|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n{{Main|Committee Against Torture (UN)}}\nThe Committee against Torture (CAT) is a body of human rights experts that monitors implementation of the Convention by State parties. The Committee is one of eight UN-linked human rights treaty bodies. All state parties are obliged under the Convention to submit regular reports to the CAT on how rights are being implemented. Upon ratifying the Convention, states must submit a report within one year, after which they are obliged to report every four years. The Committee examines each report and addresses its concerns and recommendations to the State party in the form of \"concluding observations.\" Under certain circumstances, the CAT may consider complaints or communications from individuals claiming that their rights under the Convention have been violated.\n\nThe CAT usually meets in April/May and November each year in [[Geneva]]. Members are elected to four-year terms by State parties and can be re-elected if nominated. The current membership of the CAT, {{as of|September 2017|lc = y}}:<ref name=\"CTI Members\">{{Cite web |url=http://www2.ohchr.org/english/bodies/cat/members.htm |title=Committee Against Torture \u2013 Membership |year=2009 |publisher=United Nations OHCHR |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100214131929/http://www2.ohchr.org/english/bodies/cat/members.htm |archive-date=14 February 2010 |access-date=2010-01-29 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Name !! State !!  Term Expires\n|-\n|Ms. Essadia BELMIR (Vice-Chairperson) || {{flag|Morocco}} || 31 December 2021\n|-\n|Mr. Diego RODR\u00cdGUEZ-PINZ\u00d3N || {{flag|Colombia}} || 31 December 2021\n|-\n|[[Felice Gaer]] (vice-chair)  || {{flag|United States}} || 31 December 2019\n|-\n|[[Abdelwahab Hani]] || {{flag|Tunisia}} || 31 December 2019\n|-\n|[[Claude Heller Rouassant]] (vice-chair)|| {{flag|Mexico}} || 31 December 2019\n|-\n|[[Jens Modvig]] (chair) || {{flag|Denmark}} || 31 December 2021\n|-\n|Mr. Bakhtiyar TUZMUKHAMEDOV || {{flag|Russia}} || 31 December 2021\n|-\n|[[Ana Racu]] || {{flag|Moldova}} || 31 December 2019\n|-\n|[[S\u00e9bastien Touze]] (Rapporteur) ||{{flag|France}} || 31 December 2019\n|-\n|Ms. Honghong ZHANG || {{flag|China}} || 31 December 2021\n|}\n\n=== The Convention against Torture Initiative, CTI2024 ===\n\nCreated in 2014, [https://cti2024.org/ the Convention against Torture Initiative] (CTI) is a ten-year global initiative conceptualized by the Governments of [https://www.chileangovernment.cl/ Chile], [https://denmark.dk/society-and-business/government-and-politics Denmark], [http://presidency.gov.gh/ Ghana], [http://www.indonesia.cz/the-government-of-the-republic-of-indonesia/ Indonesia] and [http://www.maroc.ma/en Morocco] (Core States), and joined by [https://www.fiji.gov.fj/Home Fiji] in 2019, to support and facilitate universal ratification and implementation of [https://www.ohchr.org/EN/ProfessionalInterest/Pages/CAT.aspx the UN Convention against Torture] (UNCAT) by 2024. To help achieve its ambitious goals, the CTI identifies and addresses challenges and barriers to ratification and implementation of the [[United Nations Convention against Torture|UNCAT]] by harnessing international cooperation, diplomacy, dialogue, knowledge transfer, ideas and technical resources sharing to support capacity building and adaptation of best practices..\n\nSince its inception, the CTI has evolved into a comprehensive hub and global platform for countries supported by a Group of Friends comprising UN member states, NGOs, torture prevention experts, academicians and a wealth of related subject matter experts'''.\u00a0''' In February 2019, during the [https://www.ohchr.org/EN/HRBodies/HRC/RegularSessions/Session40/Pages/40RegularSession.aspx 40th session of the Human Rights Council] \u2013 and at the half-way milestone of the CTI \u2013 Fiji joined the CTI Core States, driving ratification and implementation in the Pacific and beyond. Headquartered in Geneva, Switzerland, the CTI is supported by a full-time Secretariat headed by Dr. Alice Edwards. [https://apt.ch/ The Association for the Prevention of Torture] (APT) is a strategic partner that collaborates and advises on CTI activities and events.\n\nNow at the midway point of its 10-year endeavor, CTI2024 is galvanizing efforts in the remaining five to increase awareness of the benefits of the Convention, which includes State-to-State support and encouragement, experience sharing, development of science-based tools and methodologies and sharing globally accepted best practices.\n\n=== Relevance in the 21<sup>st</sup> Century ===\nThe reality is, no country is immune from torture and other abuses to its citizenry. The persistence of torture and various forms of abuse and ill-treatment \u2013 and governments\u2019 willingness to use such damaging methods of interrogation and control \u2013 demands a robust, sustained and viable response. Despite punitive sanctions coupled with the threat of being labelled a pariah state and international condemnation, abuses continue to be perpetrated in myriad countries across all regions of the globe. In some countries, the abuses are clear; in others, systems of justice lack clearly defined, stringent safeguards and institutional structures that act as deterrence, which can result in incidences and patterns of unacceptable behavior.\n\nOn 26 June 1987, [https://www.ohchr.org/EN/ProfessionalInterest/Pages/CAT.aspx the United Nations adopted the Convention against Torture and Other Cruel, Inhuman or Degrading Treatment or Punishmen]t, known as [[United Nations Convention against Torture|UNCAT]].  UNCAT aims to prohibit, prevent and respond to torture and other acts of cruel, inhuman, and degrading treatment or punishment in every nation-state. The UN Convention reinforces that torture is never justified, under any circumstance. The 1984 adoption of UNCAT was a landmark victory in the global fight against torture and ill-treatment.\n\n[[United Nations Convention against Torture|UNCAT]] goes beyond policies and protocols and is arguably the most practical of the other global human rights treaties. It offers a practical, actionable framework for integrating institutional, legislative and executive measures to combat lacunae in laws and practices and respond to government excesses. Acknowledging that some countries lack the knowledge, experience and pragmatic means of putting the treaty into practice at home, the CTI provides operational advice, tools, training and resources to assist decision-makers and public authorities in halting, preventing and safeguarding against torture and ill-treatment. Consequently, the CTI provides the means of making ratification effective before and after signing, buttressed by a package of support and resources for newly ratifying countries.\n\nAs CTI reaches its five year anniversary, the initiative is partnering with governments to reinforcing efforts to build and sustain rule of law and the fair and effective administration of justice in their home countries through technical support for infrastructure building, sharing evidence-based recommendations, best practices, institutional engagement among others. As the primary facilitator of government-to-government dialogue, and the only state-led initiative of its kind, CTI is a hub for the convening of a wide range of stakeholders including government ministers, civil society members, scholars, legal and law enforcement officials, and other related experts and stakeholders. To date, the achievements of CTI are impressive, with 15 new ratifications in five years, the attendance of over 140 governments at ministerial or senior official level at CTI regional events and seminars; and the implementation of over 80 good practices within various countries.\n\n==== Benefits ====\nImplementable tools and resources<ref name=\"Why Ratify\">{{Cite web |url=https://cti2024.org/en/why-ratify-uncat/ |title=CTI Convention against Torture Initiative {{!}} 10 good reasons to ratify UNCAT |website=cti2024.org |access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n* Dialogue and government-to-government engagement\n* International Cooperation and Diplomacy\n* Experience and Idea Sharing\n* Technical Support and Capacity Building\n* Awareness raising\n* Seminars, activities and conferences\n\n==== History of CTI ====\nIn commemoration of the 30th anniversary of the adoption of the UN Convention against Torture and with the desire to do something more profound to combat torture and ill-treatment, the CTI was launched at a high-level event during the [https://www.ohchr.org/EN/HRBodies/HRC/RegularSessions/Session25/Pages/25RegularSession.aspx 25th session of the Human Rights Council] in Geneva.\n\nIn late 2013, the regionally diverse governments of Chile, Denmark, Ghana, Indonesia and Morocco (known as the CTI Core States) emphasised the need for more rigorous, practical, real world efforts that protect all persons from torture, forms of abuse and ill-treatment throughout the world. Launched in 2014 during a high-level meeting of [https://www.ohchr.org/EN/HRBodies/HRC/RegularSessions/Session25/Pages/25RegularSession.aspx the 25th session of the Human Rights Council] in Geneva. CTI is a unique, innovative initiative that supports and enables governments to better protect individuals from torture and ill-treatment.\n\nAchieving [https://www.cti2024.org/en/objectives/ CTI objectives] is dependent on governments\u2019 openness and willingness to exchange, learn from and apply new methodologies, and to view adhering to international obligations as means to enjoy multiple direct and indirect benefits at national and local levels. On 19 December 2015, during [https://www.un.org/en/ga/search/view_doc.asp?symbol=A/RES/70/146 the UN General Assembly's 72nd session], the work of the Convention against Torture Initiative was welcomed and acknowledged  in its biannual resolution, which contains agreed standards by UN Member States. CTI\u2019s achievements have been praised in [http://ga2017.com/resolutions/english the General Assembly\u2019s 2017 resolution] and during the UN Human Rights Council biannual resolutions of 2016 and 2018.\n\nCTI released its [https://cti2024.org/en/cti-strategy-2016-17/ first strategy] covering the period 2016\u201327; its [https://cti2024.org/en/cti-strategy18-20/ second strategy] which covered the 2018\u201320 period and in March 2020, [https://cti2024.org/en/news/cti-2020-22-updated-strategic-plan/ the third strategy].\n\n==== Structure of CTI ====\n{{directory|section|date=April 2020}}\nHeadquartered in Geneva, Switzerland, CTI\u2019s efforts and activities ensue under the auspices of six core nations: Chile, Denmark, Fiji, Ghana, Indonesia and Morocco. CTI operates through the six Core States\u2019 permanent missions in New York and supported by their capitals and vast network of diplomatic representations in other countries. CTI is a truly inter-governmental, cross-regional endeavor.\n\nThe initiative is supported by a full time Secretariat, headed by Dr. Alice Edwards [LINK TO BIO], designated to provide strategic, policy and technical advice to the core States and Friends. The Secretariat is also responsible for guiding the annual programme of activities that includes:\n\n* Increasing awareness of ratification benefits\n* Developing and disseminating useable, practical tools\n* Understanding, analysing and exploring challenges and opportunities for implementation\n* Promoting greater state-to-state engagement and collaboration\n* Coordinating, designing and participation in CTI programmes and regional events and seminars, diplomatic and technical in-country visits and \u00a0workshops, study visits to Geneva for visiting inter-ministerial delegations and other events\n* Hosting platform for information and knowledge dissemination through [https://cti2024.org/ CTI\u2019s website], www.cti2024.org.\n\n<br />The CTI Secretariat supports States in the following ways:\n\n* Remote help desk that confidentially responds to technical queries\n\n* Referral service connecting States\u2019 requests for implementation support to appropriate partners and friends, where the CTI Secretariat is not best placed to support or advise\n* Partnerships with a diverse range experts with the latest developments, knowledge, analysis and expertise that enhance CTI\u2019s work\n\nCTI is buttressed by the vast knowledge and expertise of a dedicated [https://cti2024.org/en/group-of-friends/ Group of Friends] operating in Geneva and New York and through diplomatic representations in other countries. [https://cti2024.org/en/group-of-friends/ Group of Friends] (GoF) comprise UN Member States, torture prevention experts, academicians, and non-governmental (NGO) and regional organizations, members of academia, all come together to share knowledge, experience, expert advice, support and ideas on effective ways to overcome obstacles and challenges that hinder ratification and implementation of UNCAT.\n\nMembership in the Group of Friends (GoF) does not require specific obligations or commitments. Friends are free to determine how and to what extent they wish to engage in and support the CTI \u2013 at any time. CTI\u2019s GoF provide assistance through active engagement in CTI meetings, training, knowledge sharing, and seminars, high level meetings as well as support and encouragement of states moving towards ratification and effective implementation of the UNCAT.\n\nClick here for more information on CTI\u2019s [https://cti2024.org/en/group-of-friends/ Group of Friends].\n\nTo express interest in joining [https://cti2024.org/en/group-of-friends/ CTI Group of Friends], send a letter or email to the CTI Secretariat.\n\n'''Address''': CTI World Meteorological Organisation; 7bis Avenue de la Paix 2nd floor, 1202 Geneva Switzerland\n\n'''Phone''': +41 (0)22 730 86 39/47\n\n'''Email''': info@cti2024.org\n\n==== Vision ====\n\nAt CTI\u2019s launch in 2014, the Core States set out their vision: \u201cWe want, once and for all, to remove torture from the toolkit of terror and oppression and to put an end to the profound traumas and societal wounds caused by this violent practice.\u201d<ref name=\"CTI Objectives\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.cti2024.org/en/objectives/ |title=CTI Convention against Torture Initiative {{!}} Objectives |website=www.cti2024.org |access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\nBy the fortieth anniversary of the UNCAT in 2024, universal ratification will be a reality and the risk of torture and ill-treatment will be reduced as all States parties will be actively working to implement the Convention.\n\n===== Objectives =====\n<ref name=\"CTI Objectives\"/>\n* Identify and address challenges and barriers to ratification and implementation of the UNCAT through inter-State cooperation, assistance and dialogue\n* Become a hub for sharing knowledge and good practices between governments.\n* Build a global platform of States, the UN, national and international NGOs and experts to work jointly to achieve the CTI vision.\n\nThe CTI works by a principled framework of action consisting of three fundamental operating principles:\n\n===== Constructive =====\nThe CTI is an initiative created by States for States, through which experiences and best practices can be shared in a constructive manner. CTI operates under the core guiding principle of states\u2019 ability to achieve progress through dialogue, cooperation, knowledge transfer, sharing of best practices and experience and other methods. Purposefully, CTI does not name or shame governments into action. Rather, CTI relies on political willingness, understanding, and constructive and respectful dialogue. This collaborative approach allows States to discuss sensitive issues they may not otherwise discuss in other settings.\n\n===== Twinning =====\nCTI seeks to facilitate exchange of experiences and knowledge transfer among States encourage and support learning from others with similar challenges, through regional or sub-regional settings.\n\n===== Inspirational =====\nCTI aims to inspire, facilitate and motivate States progress toward ratification by highlighting \u00a0countries\u2019 \u00a0positive experiences through peer-to-peer bilateral and multilateral engagement and the development of practical, actionable tools.\n\nThe CTI is proud and encouraged by the many significant progress to date, including 15 new ratifications, the attendance of over 140 governments at ministerial or senior government official levels, at CTI regional events and seminars and the implementation of over 80 CTI best practices in various countries.\n\n===== Relations with United Nations =====\nWorking with UN Member States, CTI works to galvanise and deepen support for the UN Convention against Torture \u2013 both inside and outside the mechanisms of the United Nations. Based in Geneva, the human rights home of the United Nations, the CTI capitalises on bilateral and multilateral opportunities for awareness-raising, information-sharing and promoting ratification'''<sup>[1]</sup>''' and implementation of UNCAT through the various UN fora. This includes [https://www.ohchr.org/EN/HRbodies/HRC/Pages/Home.aspx the UN Human Rights Council], [[Universal Periodic Review|the Universal Periodic Review]] (UPR), and the deliberations of the various UN torture-relevant bodies, namely the UN Committee against Torture (UNCAT), the Sub-Committee on the Prevention of Torture [LINK: <nowiki>https://ijrcenter.org/un-treaty-bodies/subcommittee-on-prevention-of-torture/</nowiki>, the UN Special Rapporteur on Torture [LINK: <nowiki>https://ijrcenter.org/un-special-procedures/special-rapporteur-on-torture-and-other-cruel-inhuman-or-degrading-treatment-or-punishment/</nowiki>], and [https://www.ohchr.org/EN/Issues/Torture/UNVFT/Pages/WhattheFunddoes.aspx the UN Voluntary Fund for Victims of Torture]. CTI also collaborates with relevant divisions of [https://www.ohchr.org/EN/pages/home.aspx the Office of the High Commissioner for Human Rights] (OHCHR), in Geneva and throughout the world, to identify synergies and opportunities.\n\nCTI also interacts with the Third Committee, '''of''' the UN\u2019s General Assembly, which sets and discusses agenda items relating to a range of social, humanitarian affairs and human rights issues that affect people all over the world. CTI\u2019s work is also recognized and included as relevant agendas items on Committees for security, counterterrorism, policing and development. \u00a0CTI also \u00a0takes advantage of the numerous benefits of the UN\u2019s centrally located in New York is also a key location for bilateral discussions with UN Member States that do not have permanent missions in Geneva.\n\nThe work of CTI has been welcomed and acknowledged in multiple UN resolutions, a rare example of acknowledgement and appreciation to non-UN entities. Indeed, CTI is now a regular feature in the [https://www.un.org/en/ga/search/view_doc.asp?symbol=A/RES/70/146 UN General Assembly biannual resolutions], see [https://www.un.org/securitycouncil/sanctions/2206/resolutions 2015 and 2017 resolution] and by the [https://www.un.org/en/sections/documents/general-assembly-resolutions/index.html UN Human Rights Council biannual resolutions of 2016 and 2018].\n\n'''[https://cti2024.org/en/news/cti-2020-22-updated-strategic-plan/ CTI 2020\u20132022 STRATEGY]'''\n\nIn March 2020, CTI launched its third strategy, covering the period 2018\u201320, in which the CTI Core States committed to increasing awareness of the benefits of UNCAT, of sharing good State practices, as well as strengthening our institutional engagement with government ministries and other relevant stakeholders. CTI plans to enhance its capital level engagement through a bolstered programme of diplomatic and technical support visits, as well as seminars and other related activities to raise awareness and increase states\u2019 knowledge, technical capacity, showcasing best practices and share challenges and solutions in confidential settings. Additionally, CTI core states bring to bear the full weight of their diplomatic presence and reputations in spirit of international cooperation and support of CTI efforts toward states ratification and implementation, in Geneva and New York, as well as through awareness raising activities as part of regional organisations. Increased focus centers on engagement with states on their voluntary commitments made as part of the [https://www.ohchr.org/en/hrbodies/upr/pages/uprmain.aspx United Nations\u2019 Universal Periodic Review process].\n\n===== Read the CTI 2020\u201322 Strategy [https://cti2024.org/en/news/cti-2020-22-updated-strategic-plan/ here]. =====\n\n==== Benefits of Ratification ====\n{{essay-like|section|date=April 2020}}\nThe Committee argues that states [https://www.cti2024.org/en/why-ratify-uncat/ benefit from UNCAT] ratification in significant ways.<ref name=\"Why Ratify\" />\n\n# Guidance through an incremental process of improvements towards effective torture prohibition, prevention, punishment and redress for victims.\n#Access to practical, actionable steps in the prevention of torture and ill-treatment or punishment, while giving nations enough flexibility to tailor them to individual national and cultural context.\n#Conveys a powerful message of unity of conviction and vision between the nation and the International Community that torture is intolerable under any circumstances.\n#Strengthens states\u2019 rule of law and the administration of justice by facilitating effective law enforcement while enabling safer and more well-managed prisons. This promotes stability, economic investment and achievement of Sustainable Development Goals, particularly SDG16.\n#Provides a unique opportunity to redefine the relationship between the nation and its citizens. This allows a trusted, neutral space for governments to correct historic or more recent incidents of violence and discriminatory policies, abolish harmful practices, and give voice to victims of abuse, human rights violations and forms torture to speak their truth.\n#Consultations with several stakeholders to improve transparency and increase public trust in State institutions and authorities.\n#Support capacity building assistance for applicable safeguards for torture prevention and ill-treatment and provide remedies for victims. It provides an opportunity to review, improve or update existing laws, regulations, policies and procedures.\n#Impetus for enhanced training of law enforcement and other actors and allows for exchanges between nations on best practices and challenges to implementation.\n#Builds mutual trust and confidence between nations, which is particularly relevant in non-refoulment and extradition.\n# Greater international support for necessary domestic reforms in relevant sectors.\n\n'''[https://cti2024.org/en/cti-tools/ CTI TOOLS AND RESOURCES]'''\n\nThe CTI offers comprehensive, implementable [https://cti2024.org/en/cti-tools/ tools] and [https://cti2024.org/en/cti-tools/ resources] that support and advise governments on ratification, implementation and reporting.\n\n=====Implementation=====\nCTI has worked with human rights and torture prevention experts, scholars and specialists and others to create a suite of tools, resources and guides that assist \ngovernment officials and other decision makers to better understand UNCAT and the ratification process and reinforce states\u2019 ability to effectively implement the Convention\u2019s obligations in their home states. CTI\u2019s Tools and Resources enables the transfer of knowledge through sharing the benefits and challenges of ratification, latest developments in anti-torture, education and training materials and more.\n\nThe CTI Suite of Tools and Resources include:<ref name=\"CTI Tools\">{{Cite web |url=https://cti2024.org/en/cti-tools/ |title=CTI Convention against Torture Initiative {{!}} CTI tools |website=cti2024.org |access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n* [https://cti2024.org/content/images/CTI%20Ratification%20tool%20-%20executive%20action%20and%20annexes%20compilation%20Nov%202018_V3.pdf Ratification Tool] [OPCAT\n\n* What is UNCAT and why it\u2019s Relevant\n\n* Benefits and Obligations of UNCAT\n* What is OPCAT and How it Helps Ratification\n* FAQs and Supplemental Material\n* [https://cti2024.org/en/cti-uncat-implementation-tools/ UNCAT Implementation Tools]\n\nThe CTI\u2019s series of practical [https://cti2024.org/en/cti-uncat-implementation-tools/ Implementation Tools] provide support and guidance to States before, during and after UNCAT ratification. State policymakers benefit from global best practices on various anti-torture and human rights related themes as they develop or revise context-specific strategies, mechanisms and procedures for effective implementation of the UNCAT.\n\n[https://cti2024.org/en/cti-uncat-implementation-tools/ The UNCAT Implementation Tools] include:\n\n* Safeguards in the first hours of police custody\n** Handling Complaints and investigations\n** National anti-torture strategies and action plans\n** Non-coercive investigative interviewing\n** Procedures and safeguards for the principle of non-refoulement\n** Cooperation on extradition\n** Rehabilitation to victims and survivors\n** Reporting and follow-up to the UN Committee against Torture\n\n* [https://cti2024.org/en/anti-torture-law-guides/ APT-CTI Anti-Torture Law Guide]\n\nThe Law Guide comprise legislative guidance and examples on laws and amendments required to meet Convention obligations and is specifically crafted for State officials, legal advisers and drafters of legislation. The CTI Law Guide also includes an overview of anti-torture legislation in Latin America and the Caribbean in English and Spanish\n\n* Journey to Ratification: States\u2019 [https://cti2024.org/en/cti-blogs-2/ Success Stories and Experiences]\n** Prepared by the CTI Secretariat, this series of CTI blogs share inspirational stories and experiences of States journey toward ratifying the UNCAT and/or its Optional Protocol (OPCAT).\n* [https://cti2024.org/en/cti-videos-short-films/ CTI Videos and Film Shorts]\n\n* [https://cti2024.org/en/cti-training-material/ CTI Compilation of Education and Training Materials] '''[https://cti2024.org/en/cti-training-material/]'''\n** The CTI has compiled and published capacity building and training materials to assist and educate States officials on best practices in implementing the UNCAT and to increase public awareness on their rights under the Convention.\n\nFor more information on CTI tools and resources or technical queries, please contact CTI's remote help desk at info@cti2024.org.\n\n.\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Psychological torture]]\n* [[European Convention for the Prevention of Torture and Inhuman or Degrading Treatment or Punishment]]\n* [[International Day in Support of Victims of Torture]]\n* [[International Rehabilitation Council for Torture Victims]]\n* [[Use of torture since 1948]]\n* [[World Organization Against Torture]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{wikisource|Uni